[normal] Helpful Hints for Bereaved complainants going through the NHS
[normal] 
[normal]Complaints System
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] You witnessed negligence, your r
[normal]elative died a sad and difficult
[normal] 
[normal]death, but be warned,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] as you emerge from
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] the funeral service .....these forces are already aligned against you.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Health Boards
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1. The medical staff, who lie, as they wish to keep their jobs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Human nature really. 
[normal]Who could complain?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]..Well, you could.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Because 'complain' is what the NHS says that you are doing -
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] even if
[normal] 
[normal]you just want to know what happened, who was to blame and stop it
[normal] 
[normal]happening to anyone else.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]From that point on, think if yourself as a ta
[normal]rget.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Should you choose the Complaint system?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]If you don't sue, and trustingly take your case through the Ombudsman,
[normal] 
[normal]you will be badly out of pocket. So, if you are poor, don't bother.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Because,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] even if your case is upheld, it will end up on some obs
[normal]cure
[normal] 
[normal]website. Which nobody reads.... Well, maybe you.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Even worse, nobody is held accountable and the names of those negligent
[normal] 
[normal]are not included in the final report. They will be free to carry on regardless
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] in their careers. And you will be able to see th
[normal]ose ultimately responsible happily in ever better-paid NHS jobs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This is because the Ombudsman only has the power to recommend change
[normal] 
[normal]and cannot hold the authority to account.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Faint criticism
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In effect, the Ombudsman's power is to
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] say: 'Tut'.
[normal]Sometimes, a very cross
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Ombudsman even raises his/ her game to a:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]'Tsk, tsk,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]For this small outcome -
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] and going it alone without a lawyer -
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] you could
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] face:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]*
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Disbelief
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] of everything that you didn't happen to photograph
[normal]*
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Personal criticism as 
[normal]to your motivations
[normal]*
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Being played by professional NHS game players
[normal]*
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Be ignored
[normal]*
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Being lied to and lied about
[normal]*
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Shouted at by the more aggressive caseworkers
[normal]*
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] And, eventually,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] possibly years later, and having clawed your way up to the top rung of 
[normal]the complaints ladder...arrogantly dismissed, without explanation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The plus
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]On the plus side, the board chief executive could be embarrassed enough to make some improvements for patients if your case has been covered in the press.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2. The complaints
[normal] person - whilst simultaneously making soothing noises to you, promptly relays your complaint to an external professional
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]company, employed to defend the NHS and advise the Board on how make you go away.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Tactics
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A common tactic by complaints persons 
[normal]is to answer their own questions....whilst ignoring yours. This strategy will be repeated at every stage of your journey.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]So get used to it....and expect
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] it. It's designed to annoy you enough in the sincere hope that you will
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] go away - so that any NHS 
[normal]negligent death care can just carry on 
[normal]u
[normal]nnoticed as before.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Example:
[normal]Q. 'Who has authority over the deceased's body?'
[normal]A. 'In answer to your question:....Enclosed you will find our guide to the mortuary temperatures and gurneys'.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Paperwork ping-pong
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The complaints person will try and fob
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] you off by ping-ponging your requests for information in an attempt to tire you out.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Don't be tempted to tear up letters which say:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 'I hope this has been helpful' after you have even been driven to using a 
[normal]magnifying glass in the vain hope of finding any tiny thing of help.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Just laugh at this cynical
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] double-speak with the rest of the complainants, amongst whom it is now notorious.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Health Boards can also legally withhold crucial files - which you may
[normal] never know exist -
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] if they assess it in your 'best interests'
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] not to receive them.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Nb For 'your best interests' read 'their best interests'.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]If you argue that certain files must logically exist and you are legally entitled to them
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] ...they may be sud
[normal]denly found with an apologetic note on 'photocopying errors'.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Or they have suddenly 'gone missing'.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It's no use asking why important details have been changed ..ie time of death..with no counter-signature,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] because everything will be put down to a 'pape
[normal]rwork error'.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Seemingly a 'paperwork error' is a get-out-of-jail card for all medical negligence.
[normal]As it is the board's strategy is to be blamed by 'Tut' for 'substandard paperwork', rather than 'Tsk, Tsk'd'
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] for medical negligence.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Legal knowledge is
[normal] necessary
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The key here is to know that you might eventually get the files/answers, by extreme perseverance, around the six month mark.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]However, if you are not an expert in the Access to Health Records Act, Freedom of Information Act and Data Protectio
[normal]n Act and gave to learn about such things, your work hours will
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] increase on this low estimate.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This complexity makes it almost impossible for you to avoid employing a lawyer.
[normal]Clever compo-seekers will have gone this route from the start.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The 
[normal]Health Board hopes that you can't afford one.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Because you are grieving, nice and still trying to understand what went wrong and don't want to sue anyone...
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Unfortunately,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] the board sees the sign invisible which reads: SUCKER!
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
